        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>P.S. As I thought it would be most disagreeable to meet Mr. Mivart in London, without a clear understanding of the terms on which we are to stand, I have written him a formal letter, stating his grave offences, and saying that I should never hold any communication with him for the future, and signing “your obedient servant”<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The date is established by the relationship between this letter and the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9812.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to St G. J. Mivart, 12 January 1875</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">CD had written to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_3350.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">St George Jackson Mivart</ref> about an article Mivart had written in the course of which Mivart claimed that <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1224.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">George Howard Darwin’s</ref> views condoned immorality; see the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9812.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to St G. J. Mivart, 12 January 1875</ref>.</note>
        </div>        
            
